headline: OLYMPICS; The Hidden Tests on the Men's Downhill
label: https://www.nytimes.com/sports/
description: The men's course in Sestriere Borgata has a series of difficult elements in store for the skiers in tomorrow's downhill. During Thursday's training run, Daron Rahlves of the United States had the fastest time. Here is a look at Rahlves negotiating some of the tricky spots near the top portion of the run.   JOE WARD    FALLAWAY TURNS  The terrain beneath the skier slopes in the opposite direction of the turn. It can pull the skier away from his intended path and slow his run.    NAVIGATING THE FALLAWAY  Instead of skiing down the slope, Rahlves must cut across. Body is tilted parallel to the slope. Weight is Balanced entirely on the inside edge of one ski.    HIDDEN KNOLLS  Dozens of well-disguised bumps can cause racers to become airborne. Downhillers try to minimize time in the air.    SIDEHILLS  The many sidehill slopes force racers to think constantly about what the fastest route down the mountain is.    TREACHEROUS START  The top of the course has been injected with water, making it very hard and icy. It is the steepest part of the course.

headline: THE NATION: ETHICS AND CONGRESS; Where There's a Bill, There's a Way
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Congressional leaders of both parties made high-profile efforts last week to improve public confidence in the ethical standards of Capitol Hill. Stung by ever more revelations about the activities of the Republican lobbyist Jack Abramoff, they sought to show that they're dismantling a culture favorable to influence peddling.     As the week ended, proposals were still being revised, with the all-important fine print yet to be written. But the broad outlines of their ideas, scrutinized by government watchdog groups, still presents loopholes for lobbyists who press legislators for favors. (Some individual members of Congress are proposing tougher laws that would eliminate some of these loopholes.)

headline: Making Connections at the Skybox
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: All Washington is waiting for the details of a reported plea agreement with Jack Abramoff, the influential Republican lobbyist who is facing multiple investigations; a deal could be reached soon. In the world of Washington power brokers -- some would say influence peddlers -- his stadium and arena skyboxes were often stages for favors given and returned among lobbyists and legislators. Mr. Abramoff, left, had four skyboxes in the capital area: one each in the MCI Center in Washington and Baltimore's Oriole Park at Camden Yards, and two in FedEx Field, where the Redskins play. His aeries were leased mostly with money from Indian tribe clients, who paid Mr. Abramoff and his partner a total of more than $80 million to influence Congress on matters of casino gambling.

headline: So, Guy Walks Up to the Bar, and Scalia Says...

But until October 2004, justices were not identified by name, making it impossible to construct a reliable index of judicial wit.

headline: THE NATION; Republican vs. Republican
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Congress is getting unruly. Last week, the once-disciplined G.O.P. suffered a split over civil liberties, pitting President Bush and the party's leadership against the suddenly considerable weight of a handful of rebels. Four senators joined Democrats in a successful filibuster against renewal of the USA Patriot Act, set to expire this week, unhappy with some of its anti-terror tactics. News that the president authorized secret domestic eavesdropping by the National Security Agency only sharpened their worries and doomed renewal this year.

label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/

''How many Iraqi citizens have died in this war?'' he was asked after a speech in Philadelphia. His reply: ''I would say 30,000, more or less, have died as a result of the initial incursion and the ongoing violence against Iraqis.''

headline: The Basics; Uptick for a Rough Second Term
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: President Bush got some good news last week: His ratings improved, somewhat, in the latest New York Times/CBS News poll. Forty percent approved of his job performance, up from 35 percent in November, his worst showing. Of the most recent two-term presidents, only Richard M. Nixon had a lower approval rating at the same point in his presidency. And last month's 57 percent Bush disapproval rate came perilously close to President Nixon's in December 1973, after news broke of an 18 3/5rsaquo 4/5-minute gap in a White House tape recording that was central to the Watergate investigation.

headline: The Basics; Who Spoke to Woodward?
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Washington has a new guessing game, thanks yet again to the C.I.A. leak scandal. Sometime in mid-June of 2003, the first known talk of Valerie Wilson's identity as a C.I.A. operative occurred between an official and a journalist. Bob Woodward of The Washington Post came forward as the journalist, but who was his source? Among those who may have been in a position to know about Ms. Wilson, there are plenty of denials -- some of them shown below -- and others who haven't denied involvement, at right.

headline: The Basics; When Did They Know It?
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Last week, Bob Woodward of The Washington Post revealed that he was among the first journalists to discuss the identity of Valerie Wilson, the covert C.I.A. operative, with Bush administration officials. The disclosure ensured that officials will be checking their 2003 datebooks very carefully. Further investigation of the leak will surely focus on the period from June to July 2003, when the first rumors and interviews began.   BILL MARSH

headline: IDEAS & TRENDS; When Criminal Charges Reach the White House
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: THE C.I.A. leak case could bedevil the Bush administration for months. So far, however, it has not nearly approached the scale of an earlier White House scandal, Iran-contra, and its 11 convictions. The sweep of the Watergate scandal is in a class by itself. Since then, special prosecutors have taken aim at people tied to government's highest offices more than 20 times. Some inquiries, months or years long and costing millions, have found nothing to prosecute. Ronald Reagan's labor secretary, Raymond J. Donovan, was investigated for allegations of mob ties; Reagan's attorney general, Edwin Meese III, was accused of financial improprieties. Neither was indicted. After six years, prosecutors could not prove that Bill and Hillary Clinton's Whitewater real estate venture involved any criminal behavior or attempt to conceal evidence.

headline: THE NATION; In Power And Under Siege
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: WITH an announcement likely soon in the case involving the leak of a C.I.A. operative's name, worry among Republicans about the effects of several investigations is at a peak.     There is much to keep track of: in the C.I.A. case, the special counsel's scrutiny of conversations between White House officials and journalists; in the money-laundering and conspiracy charges against Representative Tom DeLay, questions about the funneling of corporate money to Republican candidates; in the investigation of the Republican lobbyist Jack Abramoff, accusations of improper dealings with Indian tribes, among other things.

headline: THE NATION; Here Is Your New Federal Credit Card. Here Is Your New Purchase Limit.
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: THE government buys everything from warships to paper clips, the latter being an example of a ''micropurchase.''     Before this month, micropurchasing with government-issued credit cards meant anything up to $2,500 on a single shopping trip, with certain purchases relating to homeland security allowed to reach $15,000 domestically and $25,000 abroad.

headline: What Will It Take to Safeguard New Orleans?
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: NEW ORLEANS has long lived with the hurricane protection that it, and the nation, were willing to pay for. Measured against the costs of Katrina's fury, however, better armor may suddenly seem more affordable.     With officials vowing to rebuild New Orleans, the question of how fully to defend the city against another catastrophe will be examined as never before.

headline: TENNIS; Wheelchair Tennis: The Basics
label: https://www.nytimes.com/sports/
description: Wheelchair tennis makes its competitive debut at the United States Open today. While the rules are similar to the ones used by able-bodied athletes, wheelchair players are allowed two bounces. Esther Vergeer of the Netherlands demonstrates the style and strategy of play.  By BEDEL SAGET    STRAPS  Over the feet, femur, hips and waist allow the chair and player to move as one.    ANGLED WHEELS  For increased speed, stability and turning    ANTI-TOP CASTORS  Improve balance and allow the athlete to push his or her weight forward or backward without tipping over.    Mobility Is Key  Players with the greater mobility usually have the edge, and most use patterns to simulate the lateral movement that the chair does not provide them. Vergeer explains some patterns and techniques used for the forehand and the backhand.    THE FOREHAND    THE APPROACH -- Using both hands, Vergeer moves towards the ball. To hit the ball, the racket starts low and ends over her left shoulder. To follow through on the shot, she pulls on the left wheel, which swings her body and chair through the shot.    THE RECOVERY -- Vergeer quickly circles back to the hub, turning her back to the net in the process.    THE BACKHAND    THE APPROACH -- When making contact, she stops the chair with her left hand and keeps herself parallel to the baseline.    THE RECOVERY -- Again she circles back into position at the hub.

label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Terrorist attacks on buses, railroads, subways and bridges increased during seven decades studied by the Mineta Transportation Institute at San Jose State University. It compiled lists of attacks starting in the 1920's; the most detailed reports focused on the period from the 1970's through mid-1997, which charted here. headline: The Basics; Livonian Spoken Here (for Now)
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: The European Union gained its 21st official language last week: Irish Gaelic. About 30 speakers will be hired to translate legislation and at E.U. meetings, all to help keep Ireland's native tongue from disappearing.     Europe is dotted with dying languages, some having dwindled to a few dozen speakers -- which linguists call ''hearth languages,'' used only by elders in one another's homes. Votian, in Russia, is one: With no written script and no children who speak it, Votian will vanish when its last speaker dies, probably within a decade or two.

label: https://www.nytimes.com/automobiles/
description: Searching for a gift? If a car is out of the question, perhaps a book about cars is within reach. Here are some possibilities, just in time for Father's Day:    The Complete Book of BMW  Every Model Since 1950  By Tony Lewin  Illustrated. 384 pages. Motorbooks International. $55.       Tony Lewin chronicles BMW's transformation from near-bankruptcy to its current place as one of the premier manufacturers of high performance luxury cars.

headline: The Basics; Unknown Toll of Friendly Fire
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Fratricide -- the accidental killing of fellow soldiers in war -- is difficult to quantify.    Some of these events made headlines, as with the four Canadian soldiers serving in Afghanistan who were mistakenly bombed by an American pilot in 2002. And last week, the family of Cpl. Pat Tillman, the National Football League star and Army Ranger accidentally shot by a fellow soldier, expressed anger at the military for concealing the nature of his death in Afghanistan in April 2004.

headline: Women Gain Votes (Some Even Matter)
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: Kuwait's Parliament granted full voting rights to women last week, a surprising reversal: two weeks earlier, a similar measure was defeated.    Women's suffrage has been entwined with other struggles. Canadian women won the right to vote in 1917 -- except for native Americans. They (and native men) were denied the vote until 1960. Likewise, Australia gave most women the vote in 1902, but its aboriginal population had to wait six more decades.

headline: The Story of Government Forms: A Real Page-Turner
label: https://www.nytimes.com/weekinreview/
description: TAX filers may be surprised this week to hear that they have it pretty good: their I.R.S.-mandated paperwork load is actually not so heavy. Not compared to the elderly of Wisconsin, Medicaid providers in Florida or immigrants, among others.    Consumer advocates and officials at the Office of Management and Budget, which oversees many federal forms, say that the Paperwork Reduction Act of 1995 improved many burdensome applications, especially those for children's aid. But other forms remain daunting, running many pages in length, with additional pages needed to explain it all.

This is based on the views of various Republican sources, notably Frank Luntz, the Republican pollster, who himself is controversial within his party. Different analysts prefer their own classifications, so there will be a lot here to provoke discussion.   BILL MARSH
